    fullText: "At 5:29 AM on July 16, 1945, the world changed forever when the first atomic bomb was detonated at the Trinity Site in the Jornada del Muerto desert of southern New Mexico. The explosion produced a mushroom cloud that rose 7.5 miles into the atmosphere and was visible from over 100 miles away. The heat was so intense -- roughly 14,710 degrees Fahrenheit at ground zero -- that it fused the desert sand into a new, mildly radioactive green glass that scientists named trinitite. J. Robert Oppenheimer famously recalled a line from the Bhagavad Gita: 'Now I am become Death, the destroyer of worlds.' The crater was 5 feet deep and 30 feet wide, and the steel tower holding the bomb was completely vaporized. The Trinity Site is on the White Sands Missile Range and is open to the public only two days per year, on the first Saturdays of April and October.",
