    fullText: "White Sands National Park in south-central New Mexico contains 275 square miles of brilliant white gypsum sand dunes, the largest gypsum dune field on the planet. Unlike regular quartz sand, gypsum is water-soluble, which is why gypsum dune fields are extraordinarily rare -- rain usually dissolves the mineral before it can accumulate. White Sands exists because the Tularosa Basin has no outlet to the sea, so dissolved gypsum from the surrounding mountains collects in seasonal Lake Lucero, then dries out and blows into dunes. The gypsum stays remarkably cool underfoot even in summer heat, making it one of the few deserts where you can walk barefoot in July without scorching your feet. Several unique species have evolved white coloring to match the dunes, including the bleached earless lizard and the Apache pocket mouse. The dune field is surrounded by the White Sands Missile Range, meaning parts of the park occasionally close when the military is conducting tests.",
