    summary: "The San Diego Zoo pioneered the concept of open-air, cageless exhibits that mimicked natural habitats. Before that, zoos were basically just animals in small cages looking miserable.",
    fullText: "The San Diego Zoo, founded in 1916 by Dr. Harry Wegeforth after he supposedly heard a lion roaring at the Panama-California Exposition, revolutionized how humans keep animals in captivity. It was one of the first zoos to replace barred cages with open-air enclosures that recreated natural habitats using moats and landscaping instead of bars. The zoo sits on 100 acres in Balboa Park and houses over 12,000 animals representing more than 650 species and subspecies. Its conservation programs have been instrumental in saving several species from extinction, including the California condor, the Arabian oryx, and the giant panda (which the zoo housed on loan from China for over 20 years). The zoo's annual operating budget exceeds $500 million, making it one of the largest nonprofit zoological organizations in the world. It is consistently ranked as the best zoo on the planet, which is especially impressive when you remember it exists because one guy heard a lion roar and decided to start a zoo on the spot.",
