    summary: "The Salk Institute in La Jolla was designed by architect Louis Kahn to be so geometrically perfect that twice a year, the setting sun aligns exactly with the central water channel.",
    fullText: "The Salk Institute for Biological Studies, founded by polio vaccine developer Jonas Salk in 1960, is widely considered one of the most important buildings of the 20th century. Architect Louis Kahn designed two rows of brutalist concrete laboratories flanking a central travertine marble courtyard bisected by a thin channel of water that points directly at the Pacific Ocean. Twice a year, during the equinoxes in March and September, the setting sun aligns perfectly with the central channel, turning the courtyard into a blazing corridor of golden light. Salk specifically asked Kahn to create a building worthy of a visit from Picasso. The concrete was left deliberately unfinished, and the teak wood panels age into a silver-gray patina that changes character with the light. Beyond its architectural significance, the institute remains one of the world's leading biological research facilities, with multiple Nobel laureates among its faculty.",
