    fullText: "The USS Alabama (BB-60), a South Dakota-class battleship, served with distinction in both the Atlantic and Pacific theaters during World War II, earning nine battle stars without suffering a single combat casualty. After the war, the ship was destined for the scrapyard until the citizens of Alabama raised $100,000 in nickels and dimes (much of it from schoolchildren) to save it. The 680-foot, 35,000-ton battleship was towed to Mobile Bay in 1964 and opened as a memorial park. Visitors can explore virtually the entire ship, from the cramped crew quarters to the massive engine room to the bridge where the captain commanded. The park also houses the submarine USS Drum and a collection of military aircraft. The battleship's nine 16-inch main guns could hurl 2,700-pound shells over 21 miles, and standing beneath them today gives you a visceral sense of the firepower that won the Pacific war.",
