    lng: -89.0928,
    title: "NASA Tests Rocket Engines in Mississippi's Backyard",
    summary: "The Stennis Space Center in southern Mississippi is where NASA tests all the main engines for the Space Launch System. When they fire one up, the sound carries for over 40 miles.",
    fullText: "Stennis Space Center, tucked into the bayous of Hancock County, Mississippi, is where NASA tests the most powerful rocket engines ever built. The facility was originally constructed in the 1960s to test the Saturn V engines that sent astronauts to the Moon. The government acquired a 125,000-acre buffer zone around the facility because the engine tests are so thunderously loud that they can be heard from 40 miles away and would be intolerable for anyone living nearby. Every RS-25 engine that has ever flown on the Space Shuttle was tested at Stennis, and the facility now tests engines for the Space Launch System, the rocket designed to return humans to the Moon under the Artemis program. During a full-duration engine test, the RS-25 burns through over 450,000 gallons of liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen in just eight minutes. The plume of steam generated during a test is visible from space.",
