    summary: "The Louisiana State Capitol in Baton Rouge is the tallest state capitol in the US at 450 feet. It was built by the controversial Huey Long, who was then assassinated inside it in 1935.",
    fullText: "The Louisiana State Capitol in Baton Rouge is the tallest state capitol building in the United States at 450 feet and 34 stories, and its history is as dramatic as its architecture. It was built in just 14 months in 1932 at the behest of Governor and then-Senator Huey P. Long, Louisiana's most powerful and controversial political figure. On September 8, 1935, Long was shot in the capitol's first-floor corridor by Dr. Carl Weiss, who was immediately gunned down by Long's bodyguards with 61 bullets. Long died two days later at age 42. Bullet holes from the bodyguards' fusillade are still visible in the marble walls of the corridor. Long is buried on the capitol grounds in a sunken garden beneath a bronze statue. Whether you view him as a populist champion of the poor or a dangerously authoritarian demagogue, his fingerprints are all over Louisiana to this day.",
