    lng: -85.3097,
    title: "The Battle Above the Clouds",
    summary: "The Battle of Lookout Mountain during the Civil War was fought in fog so thick that soldiers could not see the enemy. It earned the name 'The Battle Above the Clouds' because observers below could only hear the gunfire.",
    fullText: "On November 24, 1863, Union forces under General Joseph Hooker attacked Confederate positions on Lookout Mountain near Chattanooga, Tennessee. The battle took place in such heavy fog that the fighting was largely invisible to observers in the valley below, who could only hear the rifle fire echoing off the mountainside. The engagement became known as the Battle Above the Clouds, one of the most poetic names in Civil War history. The Union victory at Lookout Mountain, combined with the assault on Missionary Ridge the next day, broke the Confederate siege of Chattanooga and opened the door for Sherman's March to the Sea. Today, Lookout Mountain straddles three states -- Tennessee, Georgia, and Alabama -- and offers views of seven states on a clear day. The mountain is also home to Ruby Falls, the deepest commercial cave waterfall in the United States at 1,120 feet underground.",
    category: "history",
    year: "1863",
    imageUrl: "",
    videoUrl: "",
    location: "Chattanooga, Tennessee"
