    lng: -82.5515,
    title: "The Vanderbilt Estate That Out-Fancies Versailles",
    summary: "The Biltmore Estate in Asheville is the largest privately owned house in America with 250 rooms. George Vanderbilt built it in the 1890s and it took six years and 1,000 workers to complete.",
    fullText: "The Biltmore Estate in Asheville, North Carolina is the largest privately owned house in the United States. George Washington Vanderbilt II commissioned the 250-room French Renaissance chateau, which was designed by architect Richard Morris Hunt and sits on 8,000 acres of land landscaped by Frederick Law Olmsted, the designer of Central Park. Construction took six years, from 1889 to 1895, and employed approximately 1,000 workers. The house contains 35 bedrooms, 43 bathrooms, 65 fireplaces, an indoor swimming pool, a bowling alley, and a 10,000-volume library. The estate's original land holdings stretched 125,000 acres, much of which Vanderbilt later sold to the federal government to become Pisgah National Forest. The Biltmore is still owned by Vanderbilt's descendants and operates as a tourist attraction, winery, and hotel, drawing over 1.4 million visitors per year.",
