    title: "The First Powered Flight Happened in North Carolina, Not Ohio",
    summary: "The Wright Brothers were from Ohio but flew their airplane at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina. Both states claim the achievement, leading to a license plate rivalry that has lasted over a century.",
    fullText: "On December 17, 1903, Orville and Wilbur Wright achieved the first sustained, controlled, powered heavier-than-air flight at Kill Devil Hills near Kitty Hawk, North Carolina. The first flight lasted 12 seconds and covered 120 feet. The fourth and final flight that day went 852 feet in 59 seconds. The brothers chose the Outer Banks location for its steady winds and soft sand landing surface. This geographic fact has fueled a century-long rivalry between Ohio (where the Wrights lived and built the plane) and North Carolina (where they flew it). Ohio's license plates read 'Birthplace of Aviation' while North Carolina's say 'First in Flight.' The Wright Brothers National Memorial at Kill Devil Hills marks the exact spot of the flights. The original Wright Flyer is in the Smithsonian in Washington, D.C., satisfying neither state.",
