    summary: "Natural Bridge in Virginia is a 215-foot tall natural rock arch that Thomas Jefferson purchased from King George III in 1774. Jefferson considered it one of the most sublime views in nature.",
    fullText: "Natural Bridge is a 215-foot tall limestone arch spanning Cedar Creek in Virginia's Shenandoah Valley. Thomas Jefferson purchased the bridge and 157 surrounding acres from King George III in 1774 for 20 shillings. Jefferson was so taken with the formation that he called it 'the most sublime of nature's works' and built a small cabin near it for visitors. George Washington reportedly surveyed the area as a young man and carved his initials into the rock wall, though the authenticity of this claim is debated. The bridge was formed over millions of years as the creek eroded a tunnel through the limestone, which eventually collapsed except for the arch. The Monacan Indian nation considered it sacred. Natural Bridge served as a tourist attraction for over two centuries before being designated a Virginia state park in 2016. A U.S. highway runs across the top of the arch.",
