    lng: -77.4360,
    title: "Richmond Has More Civil War History Than It Knows What to Do With",
    summary: "Richmond served as the capital of the Confederacy from 1861 to 1865. When the city fell, retreating Confederate troops burned their own capital to keep supplies out of Union hands.",
    fullText: "Richmond, Virginia served as the capital of the Confederate States of America from 1861 until its fall in April 1865. The city was a strategic prize for the Union throughout the war, and the campaigns to capture it produced some of the bloodiest fighting in the conflict. When Confederate forces finally evacuated on April 2, 1865, they set fire to warehouses and bridges to deny supplies to the advancing Union army. The fires spread out of control and destroyed much of the city's commercial district. The Confederacy surrendered a week later at Appomattox Court House, about 90 miles west. Richmond has spent the last century grappling with this history. The city removed its famous Confederate statues from Monument Avenue in 2020. The American Civil War Museum now occupies the former Tredegar Iron Works, which produced artillery for the Confederacy. Richmond's relationship with its past remains complex and evolving.",
