    title: "Jefferson Designed His Own University and Put It on the Nickel",
    summary: "Thomas Jefferson designed the University of Virginia himself, considering it one of his three greatest achievements. The Rotunda is modeled on the Pantheon in Rome at half scale.",
    fullText: "Thomas Jefferson founded the University of Virginia in 1819 and personally designed its grounds, which he called the Academical Village. The centerpiece is the Rotunda, modeled on the Pantheon in Rome at exactly half scale. Jefferson considered the university one of his three greatest accomplishments -- the other two being the Declaration of Independence and the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom. He notably did not want 'President of the United States' on his tombstone. The original grounds, known as the Lawn, are a UNESCO World Heritage Site and consist of the Rotunda connected by colonnades to ten pavilions, each designed in a different architectural style to serve as teaching examples. Students still compete for the honor of living in the small rooms along the Lawn. Jefferson could see the university from his home at Monticello through a telescope. The Rotunda appears on the reverse of the U.S. nickel.",
