    summary: "The Golden Gate Bridge's distinctive International Orange color was supposed to be temporary primer. The consulting architect liked it so much that he lobbied to keep it. The Navy had wanted it painted black and yellow.",
    fullText: "When the Golden Gate Bridge was being constructed in the 1930s, the steel arrived coated in a red-orange primer to protect it from corrosion. The U.S. Navy wanted the bridge painted in black and yellow stripes for visibility, and other proposals suggested battleship gray. Consulting architect Irving Morrow argued that the primer color, which he named International Orange, complemented the natural surroundings and enhanced the bridge's visibility in San Francisco's frequent fog. He won the argument, and the color stuck. The bridge opened on May 27, 1937 and was the longest suspension bridge span in the world at 4,200 feet. Approximately 38 painters work full-time year-round maintaining the bridge's color -- they paint continuously, starting at one end and working to the other, then starting over. The bridge uses about 10,000 gallons of paint per year.",
