    title: "The Earthquake That Burned a City",
    summary: "The 1906 San Francisco earthquake was devastating, but it was the fire that followed that destroyed 80% of the city. The quake ruptured the water mains, so firefighters could not fight the flames.",
    fullText: "At 5:12 a.m. on April 18, 1906, a magnitude 7.9 earthquake struck San Francisco along the San Andreas Fault. The earthquake itself caused significant damage, but the real catastrophe was the fire that followed. Ruptured gas mains ignited blazes across the city, and the earthquake had also destroyed the water mains, leaving firefighters with empty hoses. The fire burned for three days and destroyed about 80% of the city, including over 28,000 buildings. An estimated 3,000 people died and more than half the city's 400,000 residents were left homeless. Refugee camps in Golden Gate Park and the Presidio sheltered tens of thousands. The city rebuilt with remarkable speed, and the reconstruction is considered one of the great feats of urban resilience. San Francisco now sits on a network of fault lines that scientists say will produce another major earthquake -- the question is when, not if.",
