    summary: "The Summer of Love in San Francisco's Haight-Ashbury neighborhood lasted from June to October 1967. About 100,000 young people showed up. By October, residents held a mock funeral for the movement.",
    fullText: "In the summer of 1967, approximately 100,000 young people converged on San Francisco's Haight-Ashbury neighborhood for what became known as the Summer of Love. The movement had been announced by a 'Human Be-In' in Golden Gate Park that January, where Timothy Leary told the crowd to 'turn on, tune in, drop out.' The neighborhood became a counterculture epicenter of psychedelic music, free love, communal living, and drug experimentation. The Grateful Dead and Jefferson Airplane lived on the same block. But the influx quickly overwhelmed the neighborhood. Overcrowding, drug problems, street crime, and disease set in fast. By October 1967, community leaders staged the 'Death of the Hippie' ceremony, a mock funeral proclaiming the end of the movement. The whole thing lasted about four months. Its cultural impact, however, reverberates through American society to this day.",
