    title: "The Valley Carved by Ice, Not Water",
    summary: "Yosemite Valley was carved by glaciers, not the Merced River. The glaciers were so massive they left behind sheer granite walls over 3,000 feet tall, including the face of El Capitan.",
    fullText: "Yosemite Valley is one of the most dramatic landscapes on Earth, a seven-mile-long, mile-wide canyon with near-vertical granite walls rising over 3,000 feet on both sides. The valley was carved primarily by glaciers during the last ice age, not by the Merced River that now runs through it. The glaciers scooped out a U-shaped valley, leaving behind the iconic formations: El Capitan, Half Dome, Cathedral Rocks, and Bridalveil Fall. El Capitan is the largest exposed granite monolith in the world, and its 3,000-foot face is considered the ultimate challenge in rock climbing. Yosemite Falls drops 2,425 feet in three stages, making it the tallest waterfall in North America. The valley was made famous by photographer Ansel Adams, whose black-and-white images of Yosemite became some of the most iconic nature photographs ever taken. The park draws about 4 million visitors per year, most of them concentrated in the valley.",
