    lng: -124.0046,
    title: "The Trees That Were Here Before Rome",
    summary: "The coast redwoods of Northern California are the tallest living things on Earth. The tallest one, named Hyperion, stands 380 feet. Some of these trees were alive when the Roman Empire was founded.",
    fullText: "The coast redwoods of Northern California are the tallest living organisms on the planet. The tallest known tree, Hyperion, was discovered in 2006 in a remote area of Redwood National Park and stands 380.3 feet -- taller than the Statue of Liberty. Some coast redwoods are over 2,000 years old, meaning they were saplings when the Roman Republic was still centuries from becoming an empire. The trees survive by capturing moisture from Pacific fog through their needles, a process called fog drip that can account for a third of their water intake. A single redwood can hold up to 34,000 pounds of water. The bark can be up to a foot thick and is almost fireproof, which is why many ancient redwoods survived centuries of natural wildfires. Roughly 95% of the original old-growth redwood forest was logged between the 1850s and the 1970s. What remains is concentrated in a string of state and national parks along the Northern California coast.",
