    fullText: "Wichita, Kansas has been the Air Capital of the World since the 1920s, and the title is not honorary -- the city genuinely builds more aircraft than any other city on the planet. Cessna, Beechcraft, and Learjet were all founded in Wichita. Spirit AeroSystems, the largest employer in Kansas, manufactures fuselages and other structures for Boeing's commercial aircraft here. At peak production during World War II, Wichita's factories produced one plane every 30 minutes. Roughly one in every two general aviation aircraft in the world was built in Wichita. The flat terrain of the Kansas plains is ideal for test flights, and the city's central location makes it a natural hub for the aviation supply chain. The aerospace industry employs about 35,000 people in the Wichita metro area. The city's entire identity is built around flight, from its airport code (ICT, for the nearby city of Independence's original airport) to its numerous aviation museums.",
