    title: "The Geographic Center of the Lower 48",
    summary: "The geographic center of the contiguous United States is near Lebanon, Kansas. There is a small stone marker in a field that virtually nobody visits, which feels appropriate for the most middle place in America.",
    fullText: "The geographic center of the contiguous 48 United States is located about 2.6 miles northwest of Lebanon, Kansas, a town of about 200 people. The spot is marked by a small limestone monument and a tiny chapel in a roadside park surrounded by farmland. Getting there requires driving on county roads through some of the most featureless terrain in North America. The marker was placed by the U.S. Coast and Geodetic Survey in 1918. Lebanon has tried to capitalize on the distinction, but the reality is that there is nothing at the center of the country except wheat fields, which is itself a kind of profound statement about America. If Alaska and Hawaii are included, the geographic center of the United States shifts to a point near Belle Fourche, South Dakota. Both towns claim center-of-the-nation status.",
