    title: "Brown v. Board Started at a Topeka School",
    summary: "The Supreme Court case that ended legal segregation in public schools began when Oliver Brown tried to enroll his daughter Linda at a whites-only school seven blocks from their house in Topeka, Kansas.",
    fullText: "In 1951, Oliver Brown attempted to enroll his daughter Linda at Sumner Elementary School in Topeka, Kansas, a whites-only school just seven blocks from their home. Instead, Linda was required to walk six blocks to a bus stop, then ride a bus for a mile to the Black school. The NAACP took the case, and Brown v. Board of Education of Topeka reached the Supreme Court, which ruled unanimously on May 17, 1954 that 'separate educational facilities are inherently unequal.' The decision overturned Plessy v. Ferguson's 'separate but equal' doctrine and is considered one of the most important Supreme Court decisions in American history. Monroe Elementary School, where Linda Brown was forced to attend, is now the Brown v. Board of Education National Historic Site. The decision did not immediately desegregate schools -- that took years of enforcement and further litigation -- but it established the legal foundation that made integration inevitable.",
