    title: "Dodge City Was Actually That Wild",
    summary: "Dodge City, Kansas was the wildest town in the Old West for about a decade. Wyatt Earp and Bat Masterson both served as lawmen there. Boot Hill Cemetery got its name because so many men were buried with their boots on.",
    fullText: "Dodge City earned its reputation as the wickedest city in America during the 1870s and 1880s when it sat at the intersection of the cattle drive trails and the Santa Fe Railroad. Cowboys arriving after months on the trail had money to burn and few inhibitions. Saloons, brothels, and gambling halls lined Front Street. The violence was real enough that the city hired Wyatt Earp, Bat Masterson, and other famous lawmen to maintain some semblance of order. Boot Hill Cemetery, perched on a hill overlooking the town, earned its name because so many of its occupants died violently and were buried with their boots still on, without the luxury of a proper funeral. The wild era lasted only about 10 years before the cattle drives ended and the town settled into its current role as a quiet agricultural center. But the mythology has proven immortal, making Dodge City synonymous with the Wild West.",
