    title: "The Oklahoma City Bombing Changed America",
    summary: "On April 19, 1995, a truck bomb destroyed the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City, killing 168 people including 19 children. It was the deadliest domestic terror attack in U.S. history.",
    fullText: "At 9:02 a.m. on April 19, 1995, a Ryder rental truck packed with nearly 5,000 pounds of ammonium nitrate fertilizer and fuel oil detonated in front of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in downtown Oklahoma City. The blast killed 168 people, including 19 children in the building's day-care center, and injured over 680 others. It was the deadliest act of domestic terrorism in American history. Timothy McVeigh, an Army veteran motivated by anti-government ideology, was convicted and executed. The attack shattered the notion that major terrorism could only come from abroad. The Oklahoma City National Memorial now occupies the site, featuring 168 empty chairs arranged in nine rows corresponding to the nine floors of the building. A reflecting pool and a surviving American elm, called the Survivor Tree, anchor the memorial. The site is one of the most powerful and somber public spaces in the country.",
