    fullText: "Nebraska is the only state in the United States with a unicameral legislature -- a single legislative chamber instead of the traditional senate and house. The change was championed by U.S. Senator George Norris, who argued that a bicameral system was redundant, wasteful, and allowed bills to die in conference committees without public scrutiny. Nebraska voters approved the switch in 1934 and the unicameral first met in 1937. The legislature has 49 members, the smallest of any state legislature, and elections are nonpartisan -- candidates do not run with party labels on the ballot. The system has been praised for its efficiency and transparency and criticized for lacking checks and balances. Despite its apparent success, no other state has adopted the model. Nebraska's state capitol building in Lincoln, a 400-foot Art Deco tower topped with a bronze statue called The Sower, is one of the most architecturally distinctive state capitols in the country.",
